  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 26.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "If thou take at all thy neighbour's raiment to pledge",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Lending upon pledge, the business of our modern pawnbrokers, was not forbidden by the Jewish law; only certain articles of primary necessity were forbidden to be taken, as the handmill for grinding flour, or either of its mill-stones (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 24:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").  Borrowing upon pledge was practised largely in the time of Nehemiah, and led to very ill results. See Nehemiah ch. 5. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Thou shalt deliver it unto him by that the sun goeth down",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". The reason is given in the next verse. As it could not have been worth while to take the pledge at all, if it was immediately to have been given back for good, we must suppose a practice of depositing the garment during the day, and being allowed to have it out at night. Exodus 22:26",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "If a man should lend to one of the poor of his own people, he was not to oppress him by demanding interest; and if he gave his upper garment as a pledge, he was to give it him back towards sunset, because it was his only covering; as the poorer classes in the East use the upper garment, consisting of a large square piece of cloth, to sleep in. \"It is his clothing for his skin:\" i.e., it serves for a covering to his body. \"Wherein shall he lie?\" i.e., in what shall be wrap himself to sleep? (cf. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 24:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Deuteronomy 24:10-13",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). - With ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". God directs Himself at once to the hearts of the Israelites, and attacks the sins of selfishness and covetousness, against which the precepts in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Exodus 22:21-27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " were directed in their deepest root, for the purpose of opposing all inward resistance to the promotion of His commands. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  }
]